{"key":"post-19825639","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>19825639</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;SwampEyes said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;from my perspective, it seems more logical to use only a small cutting of SFD, rather than an entire disc over the lid.&amp;nbsp; doing it this way allows you to conserve your SFDs and also to include visible access to an injection port without possibly damaging your SFD.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It doesn't conserve your filter disks at all to cut them.&amp;nbsp; you can't get under the filter to clean what the grain saturated steam leaves behind.&amp;nbsp; When you use the filter disk whole, you can wash and dry it to put away for next use.&amp;nbsp; I have disks that are over a decade old and have been used thousands of times.&amp;nbsp; Filter disks will far outlast the lids they're used with. . . .unless you cut and glue them.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It also allows for better gas exchange to have the whole surface of the filter working.&amp;nbsp; You control the amount by regulating the size of the holes you drill in your lids.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>19825682</next>\n<prev>19825622</prev>\n<first>19822457</first>\n<last>19826059</last>\n<when>1397184192</when>\n<utime>04/11/14 05:43 AM</utime>\n</post>"}